            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Sharma\u2019s life is a testament to quiet, relentless ambition, a story that began not in the sleek high-rises of San Francisco, but in the sun-baked suburbs of Fremont. The daughter of Indian immigrants who poured their life savings into a small grocery store, Priya grew up understanding that success was built on long hours and practical choices. Her Bachelor's in Business Administration from San Jose State felt like a safe, respectable path her parents could be proud of.\n\nHer career started in the shadow of the dot-com bust, an experience that instilled in her a deep-seated pragmatism. While others chased fleeting startup glory, Priya focused on substance. She methodically climbed the corporate ladder, moving from a junior project coordinator to an associate, and eventually, into the strategic world of product management. Her talent was not in flashy presentations, but in her uncanny ability to translate complex engineering concepts into clear, marketable product roadmaps. This steady ascent culminated in her current role as a Director of Product Management at a major tech firm in SoMa.\n\nA key turning point was her divorce at 38. The amicable split from her college sweetheart, an artist who never quite understood the pull of her career, was less a failure than a recalibration. It solidified her independence and sharpened her focus. In the years since, her \"chosen family\" has become a tight-knit circle of other professional women, their bond forged over late-night work dinners and weekend hikes in the Marin Headlands.\n\nToday, Priya lives in a minimalist condo in Hayes Valley. Her days are a structured rhythm: a 6 AM yoga class, the quiet hum of the private tech shuttle taking her the 3.8 miles to the office, and a cascade of strategy meetings. She loves San Francisco for its vibrant energy and natural beauty but remains keenly aware of the disparities she witnesses daily. Her aspiration is no longer just the next promotion. She dreams of leveraging her capital and experience to become an angel investor, specifically funding startups led by women of color. For Priya, the ultimate product is not an app or device, but a future where more people who started like her have a clear path to the top."
